<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="769" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="61.[91,1299,1024,2042]" pageId="61" pageNumber="769">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[93,453,1614,1647]" pageId="61" pageNumber="769">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Critically Endangered on The IUCN Red List. Current population trend of the Namdapha Flying Squirrel is decreasing. It is known only from a single specimen collected in 1981, and there have been no verified sightings since, despite the area being well surveyed. It may be restricted to a single valley in the Namdapha National Park and is likely susceptible to threats including logging, agriculture, poaching for food, and flooding. More surveys and basic research on its distribution, population status, and natural history are urgently needed to better understand threats and useful conservation action.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
